HOW TRUMP FAILS IN UKRAINE

- NATO peace keepers work, but putting NATO forces on Russia’s border is a gift Putin NEVER wanted, nor will he accept.  
- If NATO is bad, UN peace keepers are worse. Imagine the shitstorm that ensues when Chinese ‘peace keepers’ get into a Russian/Ukraine border skirmish.   

So…. Trump’s brilliant 5 second sound bite (‘I’ll make a deal’) is utterly void of reality.  The truth is, forcing Ukraine into peace talks really means forcing them into insurgency warfare.  And forcing our European allies to covertly support Ukraine in that effort.  

The war won’t end.  It will merely morph into a different beast.  And as it continues to rage, Trump will look like a ‘loser’ who could not close the deal.

text:
This post is going to start off like a massive blackpill, but I promise it ends with a whitepill if you just keep reading.

Trump is almost certainly going to lose Virginia, but he doesn't need VA to win this election. First, let me explain why I don't believe Trump can win Virginia: 

There are too many early votes that have already been cast.

Even if we assume record turnout (over 75%, which would match 2020), we're still on track for more than 45% of the total vote to be cast early.

And while it's true that Trump will win the largest percentage of the early vote of any Republican in modern history, he's still going to lose this group.

For example, even if we have him splitting independents and swing voters (who traditionally break for Democrats in ABEV voting), he's still on track to lose the early vote 55-45.

And this is where the real problem for Trump in VA comes into play.

If we assume this generous breakdown in the early vote (which is exceedingly unlikely), AND if we assume a record turnout that breaks even 2020 levels, then Trump would still need to capture 54% of the election day vote to secure a 0.13% margin of victory in VA.

That simply isn't happening.

But now that I've dumped a bunch of cold water on my followers who have been hoping that the daily reports of Virginia getting redder would mean Trump can actually flip VA, let me provide everyone with a whitepill.

The numbers I see in Virginia—while pointing very clearly to a Harris victory here—also seem to spell trouble for her in the rest of the country.

The margins in Virginia are *objectively* moving to the right from 2020. Virginia is almost certainly not going to vote for Trump, but it WILL get redder this year.

Doing some back-of-the-napkin math brings the best case for Harris to around 8.5% in VA, and that's after giving her 2022 margins with early swing voters AND giving her an outright victory on election day in the Commonwealth (two extremely generous assumptions that seem far-fetched considering the current national environment).

Does that mean I'm officially calling VA for Harris by 8.5%? No. My original prediction for Virginia going to Harris by 5-7 has not changed. I'm simply using these figures as placeholders to demonstrate how VA is poised to shift right this year, potentially by several points.

The broader point I'm trying to make is that if Harris only wins VA by 8.5% after making these frankly absurd concessions to her, I cannot see a realistic path for her to win the presidential election. If she needs this much help to get her to 8.5% in VA, I don't see how she possibly wins states like NC, GA, or PA.

text:
To further ingratiate myself with Solana fans, here's an argument of why a Trump win and/or Republican sweep (which Polymarket has at 50%) is bearish memecoins.

i) Memecoins themselves are a form of economic populism. They are a statement against the unfair ( and often grifty) tokenomics of VC-backed and insider coins. 

ii) But VC-backed coins are a modern phenomenon forced upon us by the toxicity of the Gensler/Warren regime. As are extreme measures like geo-blocked airdrops, VPN blocks, and so on.

iii) A Republican sweep undoes all of that and brings back ICOs, airdrops for all, and other kinds of token sanity. 

iv) A Republican sweep also enables fee switches and token dividends and other economically productive ways to return value to token-holders that memecoins don't have.

Ergo: regulatory sanity in America is bad for memecoins because it refocuses crypto on dApps and other things that actually matter, leading to a prolonged bear market where most people lose money on them.

Not investment advice. Except for the part about people losing money on memecoins. That's definitely investment advice. It's inevitable no matter what happens in the election. Every joke eventually stops being funny.
